Identifying Gas Reservoir Drive Mechanism

Alwalid Albaqmi - Petroleum Engineering
Mohammed Almulhim - Petroleum Engineering

Introduction

In reservoir engineering, identification of drive mechanism is essential. The drive mechanism provides the pressure support that the reservoir needs when production starts in order to prevent collapse. Moreover, it is preliminary feature that is required to anticipate the volume of gas/oil initial in place. Therefore, to know how much gas/oil will be recovered from the reservoir, the drive mechanism must be identified.
For gas reservoirs, the identification of the drive mechanism is graphical. Havelan & Odeh Material Balance Equation (H&O MBE) is the base that governs the production and composition data so that it generates a set of data points that will be plotted eventually. The regression approach, hence, is utilized to formulate the best-fitted curve. Then, using H&O Reference Graph, the drive mechanism can be identified to be Volumetric Drive, Water Drive, or Combination Drive of both with each having its relative strength to support the reservoir.

Mathematical Model

The H&O MBE is given by the following equation,
G (Bg - Bgi) + We = Gp Bg + Wp Bw
  • G: Volume of Initial Gas in Place (SCF).
  • Gp: Volume of Cumulative Gas Production (SCF).
  • Bg: Gas Formation Volume Factor (CF/SCF).
  • Bgi: Initial Gas Formation Volume Factor (CF/SCF).
  • We: Volume of Water Encroachment (bbl).
  • Wp: Volume of Water Production (STB).
  • Bw: Water Formation Volume Factor (bbl/STB).
The equation is simplified to,
G Eg + We = F where F = Gp Bg + Wp Bw, and Eg = Bg - Bgi
  • F: Volume of Total Gas and Water Production (CF).
  • Eg: Gas Expansion Factor (CF/SCF).
The final form that will be utilized is then given by,
= G + (1)
And the Reference Graph is,

Method and Approach

To be able to identify the drive mechanism of the reservoir, two main set of data have to be obtained from the reservoir well logs or from laboratory experiments. For Sand-A gas reservoir, discovered in 1962 by Shell Oil Company, the composition data which characterizes the gas mixture that we are dealing with can be found by taking samples of the gas produced. Following table shows compositional data,
From the left, the 1st-column lists the components of the gas mixture in the reservoir, 2nd-column is the mole fraction of the component, meaning, how much of it is in the mixture. 3rd-column is the molar weight of the component. 4th and 5th columns are the thermodynamic data of each component describing its critical pressure and critical temperature, respectively.
The other set of data is the production data as shown in the following table,
where T referes to the well number, dates refer to measurement date, pressures are the reservoir pressure at that date and corresponding to the amount of gas produced at this pressure. Also, reservoir temperature given to be T = 190 F. In addition, information about the water production is readily available. For Sand-A, the water production is somewhat small which is Wp = 0.03 STB, and Bw = 0.96 bbl/STB.
The above two tables will be used to find the values of F and Eg in equation (1) corresponding to the measured values of Gp. However, other essential equations will be used along the way which are,
Bg = 0.02829 (2)
Z = Psr (-0.0284 Tsr + 0.0625) + 0.4714 Tsr - 0.0011 (3)
Psr = and Tsr = (4) and (5)
Psc = and Tsc = (6) and (7)
  • T: Reservoir Temperature (R).
  • P: Reservoir Pressure (psia).
  • Z: Gas Compressibility Factor.
  • Psr: Pseudo Reduced Pressure.
  • Tsr: Pseudo Reduced Temperature.
  • Psc: Pseudo Critical Pressure (psia).
  • Tsc: Pseudo Critical Temperature (R).
  • Xi: Mole Fraction of Component i.
  • Pci: Critical Pressure of Component i (psia).
  • Tci: Critical Temperature of Component i (R).
  • n: Total Number of Components.
Then, when F and Eg values are obtained successfully for every Gp, values will be plotted aganist Gp. However, the resulted graph will have a scattering nature that is difficult to fit. Therefore, we will use the regression approach to best-fit the scattering points until we obtain a similar curve to that of the Reference Graph of H&O MBE. Afterwards, the drive mechanism can be identified with a great extent. Possible regressions will be used including linear, polynomial of 2nd degree (quadratic), and polynomial of 3rd degree (cubic).
For the regression approach, the Least-Squares critirion will be used for all regressions.

Numerical Results and Coding

First, looking closly into equation (1), the first term is required. However, to find its value, F and Eg have to be calculated separately. From the derivation of H&O MBE explained previously, F and Eg are given by the following equations, respectively,
F = Gp Bg + Wp Bw (8)
Eg = Bg - Bgi (9)
Thus, to calculate F and Eg, Bg and Bgi must be obtained first using equation (2). However, Bg and Bgi cannot be obtained unless Z is obtained. So, to find Z, equation (3) is used. Again, Z cannot be calculated unless Psr and Tsr are obtained using equations (4) and (5). In order to calculated them, Psc and Tsc are calculated first using equations (6) and (7) plus the compositional data table. Therefore,

P=[4012 3964 2932 3966 3664 3344 3943 3256 3972 3537 3062 3833 3615 3202 3772 3674 3580 3181 3737 3615 3543 3148];

Z(i) = Psr(i)*(-0.0284*Tsr(i)+0.0625)+0.4714*Tsr(i)-0.0011;
Bg(i) = 0.02829 *(T*Z(i)/P(i));
end

Now, the data points are ready to be plotted,
plot(Gp',F_Eg','ro'); grid on;
ylabel('F/Eg (SCF)');
xlabel('Gp (MMM SCF)')
The scattering nature is obvious from the plot which makes it difficult to fit, and therefore, difficult to identify the drive mechanism. However, the regression approach will help to fit this plot to a proper curve.
Considering the regression curves that will be generated, two main criteria will be used to determine the best fitting curve. First one is the resemblance with the Reference Graph. If the curve obtained from regression differs greatly from the basic three curves in the Reference Graph, the regression is not suitable to determine the drive mechanism. Second one is Coefficient of Determination (). If two regressional curves resemble some curves in the Reference Graph, the one with the highest Coefficient of Determination is the best fitting cuvre, and can be used to identifiy the drive mechanism.
To summarize, the regressional curve must first satisfies the resemblence condition with respect to the Reference Graph. Then, if two or more regressional curves satisfy the first condition, the one with highest Coefficient of Determination is the best fitting curve.
Before proceeding to the regression curves, first values of Gp and in the above table should be eliminated from the array so that polyfit can be implemented.
F_Eg = F_Eg(2:end);
Gp = Gp(2:end);
A) Linear Regression
The regression curve can be plotted using the following code:
xx = min(Gp):0.5:max(Gp);
a = polyfit(Gp,F_Eg,1);
yy = polyval(a,xx);
plot(Gp,F_Eg,'ro',xx,yy,'-b'); grid on;
ylabel('F/Eg (SCF)');
xlabel('Gp (MMM SCF)')
The regression curve resembles the Volumetric Drive curve in the Reference Graph. Hence, satisfies the first conditon/criterion. However, Coefficient of Determination is required to compare this regression curve with other curves if they resemble the Reference Graph as well.
ybar = mean(F_Eg);
st = sum((F_Eg-ybar).^2);
yy = polyval(a,Gp);
sr = sum((F_Eg-yy).^2);
r2 = (st-sr)/st
r2 =
0.006669549193454
B) Quadratic Regression
The regression curve can be plotted using the following code:
xx = min(Gp):0.5:max(Gp);
a = polyfit(Gp,F_Eg,2);
yy = polyval(a,xx);
plot(Gp,F_Eg,'ro',xx,yy,'-b'); grid on;
ylabel('F/Eg (SCF)');
xlabel('Gp (MMM SCF)')
The regression curve resembles the Weak Water Drive curve in the Reference Graph. Hence, satisfies the first conditon/criterion. However, Coefficient of Determination is required to compare this regression curve with other curves if they resemble the Reference Graph as well.
ybar = mean(F_Eg);
st = sum((F_Eg-ybar).^2);
yy = polyval(a,Gp);
sr = sum((F_Eg-yy).^2);
r2 = (st-sr)/st
r2 =
0.211881783323874
C) Cubic Regression
The regression curve can be plotted using the following code:
xx = min(Gp):0.5:max(Gp);
a = polyfit(Gp,F_Eg,3);
yy = polyval(a,xx);
plot(Gp,F_Eg,'ro',xx,yy,'-b'); grid on;
ylabel('F/Eg (SCF)');
xlabel('Gp (MMM SCF)')
The regression curve does not resemble any curve in the Reference Graph. Hence, does not satisfies the first conditon/criterion, and cannot be used to identify the drive mechanism.

Visualization

To understand how does a weak water drive works in Sand-A reservoir, the following figure is presented,
The figure shows a 3D simulation of Sand-A gas reservoir. The 3D model is developed after extensive and intensive information gathering and calculation through the production life of the reservoir. In addition to various laboratory experiments and sample measuremnts. The model shows a thin water-bearing formation (light blue) being directly under the gas zone (red). That confims our results of the existance of water drive. However, considering the limited thickness of this water-bearing formation, and its limited water content based on the water production data, it is clealry a weak water drive. Again, confiming the results of our analysis. In reservoir engineering, the weakness is translated as being limited. Meaning, the Sand-A gas reservoir will produce most of its gas by water drive, but eventually this water drive will cease at certain time in the production life of the Sand-A. When Sand-A reaches this stage in its life, other artifical recovery method should be sought such as water injection or steam injection.

Discussion

The result of our analysis shows that Sand-A gas reservoir undergoes a weak water drive at its early life stages. The water provides support and energy for the gas production process. The next step is to determine the amount of gas that can be produced under this drive. However, H&O MBE technique cannot be relied on solely. Other methods of drive mechanism identification, both analytical and graphical, must be applied to confirm the results. In the case of Sand-A, the H&O MBE showed a great determination of the drive mechanism confirmed by the 3D model developed by the company. The regression approach plays a major role in reservoir engineering since most of this fields applications are graphical. Also, the scattering nature is usually encountered in this field.
Moreover, the results can be greatly improved by gathering more production data from the wells on periodical basis. This wil reduce the scattering behavior and eventully makes the idetification of the drive mechanism much easier. Also, the disadvatage of using this method is time. The pressure values provided are static. Meaning after producing certain amount of gas from the reservoir, the production is shut-in, and static pressure values are measured when pressure stabilizes. This is somewhat impractical in development wells for which production is the main focus. However, in exploratory wells, the main focus is to understand the reservoir better, so spending too much time to get a measurement is actually the routine.

Summary

Sand-A gas reservoir is used as a study case to determine its drive mechanism graphically using H&O MBE and the Reference Graph. Both, production data and composition data are available through well logs and laboratory experiments. The best fit curve is determined using regression approach linear, quadratic, and cubic fitting. Two conditions/criteria are used to determine the best fit regressional curve. First is the resemblance to the Reference Graph, and the second is the Coefficient of Determination. Sand-A is found to be undergoing a weak water drive. The results are confirmed by the 3D model of the reservoir. Improvments of the regression approach can be utilized if more production data are available. This method is graphically-based and widely used. However, other methods of identification should be applied to ensure a good estimaton of gas recovery from the reservoir.
